column2: Annotation(http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/creator,^^(Cathy Dolbear, John Goodwin, Glen Hart, Katalin Kovacs, Hayley Mizen,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#WaterMeadow),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Water meadow is a kind of Meadow. (d) A Water meadow is Located on a Floodplain. (d) A Water meadow Contains Water during Spring.Season. (d) A Water meadow Enables Pasture land in Spring.Season A Water Meadow Has Footprint.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#RiverBank),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A River Bank is a kind of Bank. A River Bank Is The Edge Of A Channel that contains a River. (d),http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Cataract),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Cataract Is A Kind Of Waterfall. A Cataract Is Sheer.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#DisusedCanal.Water),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A DisusedCanal.Water Is A Kind Of Body Of Water. (d) A DisusedCanal.Water is part of a DisusedCanal.Stretch. (d) A DisusedCanal.Water Is Contained In A Canal.Channel. (d) A DisusedCanal.Water does not enable Inland Navigation. (d) A DisusedCanal.Water enables fishing. DisusedCanal.Water does not have a current,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#ChannelBed),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Channel Bed Is A kind of Bed A Channel Bed Is The Bed Of A Channel. (d),http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Inlet),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(An Inlet is a kind of Body of Water. An Inlet is Located in either a Lake or a Sea or a River or Estuary. An Inlet Is part of either a Lake or a Sea or a River or Estuary. An Inlet Has Footprint. An Inlet Is An Indentation Into The Land. An Inlet has synonym Creek.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Channel),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Channel Is A Hollow In The Ground Surface or on a Structure. A Channel Has Part Bed and at least 2 Bank. A Channel Enables Containment Of Water A Channel Is Connected To A Channel, A Pipe, A Basin Or A Wetland. A Channel Has Footprint.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#TidalRiver),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Tidal River is a kind of River. (d) A Tidal River is a River that has at least 1 Tidal River Stretch. (d),http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Estuary),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(An Estuary is a kind of Body of Water. An Estuary connects at least 1 River to exactly one Sea. An Estuary is part of a Sea. An Estuary Has a Current. An Estuary Has Footprint. An Estuary has plural Estuaries.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#InfluentStream),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(An Influent stream is A kind of Stream. An Influent Stream either Flows through a Sink into a Cave or Discharges Through Chalk or Limestone. An Influent Stream Flows Over Chalk or Limestone.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Waterfall),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Waterfall is a body of Water. (d) A Waterfall is Falling Water. (d) A Waterfall is a Part of a River or a Stream. (d) A Waterfall is is located at (a Cliff or Slope or Excarpment) (d) A Waterfall Has Footprint. A Waterfall Prevents Inland Navigation. (prevents is opposite to enables) A Waterfall Has one or more Steps. A waterfall has a current,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#River),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A River is a Kind of Body of Water. A River Flows in a Channel. A River Has part At least 1 River Stretch. A River has part At least 1 Source A River has At least 1 River mouth or At least 1 Confluence. River is Tidal if At least 1 of the River stretches of the River is tidal A River Flows into a Lake, a Sea, a Reservoir or a River. A River has a current. A River is connected to a River, a Stream, a Canal, a Lake, a Reservoir, a Pond, or a Pool. A River has a Footprint. A River Has Welsh translation Afon.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#FishPond),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Fish pond is A kind of Pond A Fish pond Contains Fish A Fish pond Has primary purpose Fishing.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Cascade),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Cascade Is Kind Of Waterfall. A Cascade Flows Over at least 2 Shallow Steps Or Boulders.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Bay),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Bay is a kind of Body of Water. A Bay is Located in either a Lake or a Sea, but not both. A Bay Is part of either a Lake or a Sea, but not both. A Bay Has Footprint. A Bay Is An Indentation Into The Land.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Dam.Water),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Dam.Water Is A Kind Of Pool.InRiver. A Dam.Water Is Located Behind Dam.Structure. A Dam.Water Is Located In A River Or A Stream.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#RiverMouth),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A River Mouth is a kind of Body of Water. River mouth Is part of a River. A River Mouth connects a River to a River a Sea or a Lake. River Mouth Has Footprint. River Mouth Has synonym Mouth.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#DryCanalStretch),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A DryCanalStretch is Part of a Canal. A DryCanalStretch has part Canal.Channel. A DryCanalStretch does not has part Canal.Water. A DryCanalStretch connects to at least one Canal Stretch or at least one DryCanal Stretch. A DryCanal Stretch connects to at most 3 Things. A DryCanalStretch Has Footprint,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#TimberPond),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Timber Pond is A kind of Pond. (d) A Timber Pond Has primary purpose Storage of Timber (d) A Timber Pond is Adjacent to a River.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Ditch),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Ditch Is A Kind Of Channel. A Ditch Enables Drainage. A Ditch has synonym Trench. Ditch has plural Ditches.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Bourne),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Bourne is a Kind of Stream. A Bourne is contained in A Channel A Bourne seasonally exists during Winter. A Bourne has synonym Winterbourne.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#TypicalBalancingPond),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Balancing pond is typically adjacent to a Canal,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Marsh),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Marsh is A kind of Wetland. A Marsh does not Contain Peat. A Marsh is temporarilyflooded by Water.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Leat.Channel),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Leat.Channel Is a kind of channel (d) A Leat.Channel Contains a Leat. (d) A Leat.Channel Has primary purpose transport of water for industrial use.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Whirlpool),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Whirlpool is a kind of circular Current. (d) A Whirlpool is Located in Rivers or Seas. (d),http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#LockGate),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A LockGate is a kind of Structure. A LockGate has primary purpose control of water flow. A LockGate is part of a Canal.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Tributary),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Tributary Is a kind of a Stream or a River. (d) A Tributary Flows into either a Stream or a River. (d) A Tributary has plural Tributaries.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#DisusedCanalStretch),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Disused canal stretch is part of a Canal A disused canal stretch has part canal.channel A disused canal stretch has part disused canal.water A disused Canal Stretch connects to at least one Canal Stretch or at least one DryCanal Stretch. A disused Canal Stretch connects to at most 3 Things. A disused Canal Stretch Has Footprint. A disused canal stretch is not disjoint from a dry canal stretch,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Broad),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Broad is a Kind of Lake. A Broad is typically Located in East Anglia.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Force),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Force is a Kind of Waterfall. A Force Is A Synonym Of Waterfall In Northern England. A Force Has Synonym Foss,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Linn),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Linn is a Kind of Waterfall. A Linn is a synonym of Waterfall in Scotland.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#MillPond),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Mill Pond is A kind of Pond. A Mill Pond is Located near a Mill A Mill Pond Has primary purpose Water supply. A Mill Pond is Connected to At least one Mill race.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Bank),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Bank Is The Edge Of A Channel Or A Basin. A Bank Is Part Of A Channel Or A Basin A Bank Has footprint.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Axiom_1),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(something that has a part which contains water also contains water itself,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#TypicalBog),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Bog is typically fed by rain water,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#BodyOfWater),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Body of Water is made of Water A Body Of Water Has Footprint.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#TypicalBroad),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A broad is typically located in East Anglia,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#CanalStretch),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Canal Stretch has part Canal.Channel. A Canal Stretch has part Canal.Water. A Canal Stretch is part of a Canal. A Canal Stretch connects to at least one Canal Stretch or at least one DryCanal Stretch. A Canal Stretch connects to at most 3 Things. A Canal Stretch Has Footprint.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#MillLade),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A mill lade is a synonym for Mill Race in Scotland,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#CurlingPond),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Curling pond is a Kind of Pond A Curling pond Has primary purpose Curling,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Weir),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Weir is a kind of structure. A Weir Has Primary purpose Control of Water Flow.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Source),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A source is a kind of spring or wetland,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#NavigationalCut),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Navigational cut is A kind of Canal. A Navigational cut has exactly one Canal Stretch.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Nant),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Nant is a kind of stream A Nant is a synonym of stream in Wales,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Stream),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Stream is a Kind of Body of water. A Stream flows in a Channel. A Stream has part At least one Source A Stream flows to a River, a Stream, a Canal.water, a Lake, a Pond or a Pool or Estuary or Reservoir or a Sea or a Sink. A Stream Has Footprint. A Stream Has Welsh translation Nant. A Stream Has a Current. A Stream is not disjoint from river.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Wetland),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Wetland is a kind of Area of Land. A Wetland Is an Area that is Saturated by Water. A Wetland Has Footprint. A Wetland is Connected to a River, a Canal, a Stream, a Lake, a Pond, or a Wetland or Nothing.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Rapids),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Rapid is a Body of Water. A Rapid Is part of a River or a Stream. A Rapid Has a Footprint. A Rapid typically Prevents Inland Navigation. A Rapid has a Turbulent Current.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#DryDisusedCanalStretch),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A DryDisused Canal Stretch has part Canal.Channel. A DryDisused Canal Stretch does not have part Canal.Water or DisusedCanal.Water A DryDisused Canal Stretch is part of a Canal. A DryDisused Canal Stretch connects to at least one Canal Stretch or at least one DryCanal Stretch. A DryDisused Canal Stretch connects to at most 3 Things. A DryDisused Canal Stretch Has Footprint.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#SluiceGate),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A SluiceGate is a kind of Structure. A SluiceGate has primary purpose control of water flow. A SluiceGate is part of a Canal. A SluiceGate has synonym Sluice.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#AgriculturalDrain),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(An Agricultural drain is A kind of Drain An Agricultural drain Has primary purpose Drainage. An Agricultural Drain is adjacent to AgriculturalFields.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Pipe),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Pipe enables Transport of water. A pipe enables containment of water A Pipe is connected to a Channel, a Pipe or a Basin. A Pipe Has Footrpint.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Pool.InRiver),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Pool.InRiver is a Kind of Body of Water. A Pool.InRiver is Contained in a Body of Water. A Pool.InRivers is part of either a Stream or River A Pool.InRiver Has a Footprint. A Pool.InRiver Has no Current,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Burn),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Burn is a kind of Stream. A Burn Is A Synonym Of A Stream In Scotland Or Northern England.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Spa),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A spa is a kind of spring A spa contains mineral salts A spa has synonym Mineral Spring,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(ObjectProperty(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#flowsInto),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(flow Into is where the water discharges into the object it flows to.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#CoveredReservoir),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Covered reservoir is A kind of Reservoir. (d) A Covered reservoir has a Cover. (d),http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Reservoir),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Reservoir is A kind of Body of Water. A Reservoir Has primary purpose Water supply. A Reservoir is Controlled by At least one Dam.Structure, or Sluice Gate. A Reservoir is not disjoint with Lake an Pond.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#IrrigationDitch),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(An Irrigation Ditch Is A Kind Of Ditch. An Irrigation Ditch Has Primary Purpose Irrigation. Irrigation ditch has plural Irrigation ditches.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#CoolingPond),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Cooling Pond is A kind of Pond. A Cooling Pond Has inflowing Industrial water. A Cooling pond is Located in Industrial areas.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Lode),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Lode is A kind of Stream. A Lode is located on Embankment.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#ModelBoatLake),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Model boat lake is A kind of Pond. A Model boat lake Has primary purpose Use of model boats.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Ford),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Ford Is A Part Of A River Or A Stream. A Ford Is A Part Of A Road Or A Path or Track. A Ford Has Primary Purpose Stream crossing or River crossing. A Ford Connects Either Roads Or Paths or a Track. A Ford Has A Footprint.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Backwater),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Backwater is a Kind of Pool.InRiver. A Backwater is Located in either a Stream or a River, but not both and not anything else. A Backwater is Part of either a Stream or a River, but not both and not anything else. A Backwater has no Current.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Pool),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Pool is a Kind of Body of Water. A Pool is contained in a Basin. A Pool Has Footprint. A Pool is connected to a River, a Stream, a Canal.water or nothing. A Pond does not have a Current.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#BoatingLake),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Boating lake is Kind of Pond (d) A Boating lake Has primary purpose Boating. (d),http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Waterway),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Waterway is a kind of River or a kind of Canal.Water. (d) A Waterway Has primary purpose Inland Navigation.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Fen),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Fen is a Kind of Wetland. A Fen Contains Peat A Fen is typically Fed by Groundwater.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#Lake),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Lake is a Kind of Body of Water. A Lake is typically contained in a Basin A Lake is connected to a River, a Stream, a Canal, a Lake, or a Reservoir (one or more) A Lake Enables InlandNavigation A Lake Enables Boating or Fishing. A Lake Has a Footprint. A lake has a current Lake Has Welsh translation Llyn. Lake Has synonym Flash. Lake Has synonym Mere.,http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string)))

EntityAnnotation(Class(http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/ontology/Hydrology.owl#DykeSpring),Annotation(http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment,^^(A Dyke Spring Is A Kind Of Spring. Scope: Permanent topographic features involved in the containment and transport of surface inland water of a size of 1 metre or greater including tidal water within rivers. Purpose: To describe in an unambiguous manner the inland hydrology feature classes surveyed by Ordnance Survey with the intention of improving the use of the surveyed data by our customers and enabling semi-automatic processing of these data. Feature terms have primarily been taken from the Ordnance Survey Master Map Real World Objects Catalogue [1], however new terms have also been added in order to ensure the completeness of the domain. The feature definitions have also been taken from Ordnance Survey Master Map Real World Objects Catalogue [1] but they have been completed and modified where descriptions were insufficient. The sources of the additional definitions are noted after each definition. The ontology modules (Spatial relations, Network relations, Language relations, Political geography and Mereology) include only those relationships and concepts that were directly relevant to the Hydrology ontology. [1] Ordnance Survey (2001) Ordnance Survey Master Map Real World Objects Catalogue, v. 1.0, November 2001.
